# Security Guidelines
This document outlines security best practices for developing with Canva templates.

## Rules

**❌ NEVER:**
- Hardcode API keys, passwords, tokens, or credentials in code, comments, or documentation
- Ask users for API keys, passwords, tokens, or any credentials
- Commit secrets to version control or log credentials to console
- Run terraform commands or AWS CLI commands

**✅ ALWAYS:**
- For AI features: use the built-in `@canva-ct/genai` package (no API keys needed)
- For other API keys: instruct the user to contact #creative-tech on Slack first
- Use obviously fake placeholder data for prototypes
- Pause and ask user before adding backend functionality

## Authentication & Secrets

**This is a frontend-only application** - any API keys added here will be visible in the browser (publicly accessible to anyone).

### AI Agent Behavior

**NEVER ask users for credentials:**

The AI agent must NEVER:
- Prompt users to provide credentials, tokens, or passwords
- Request access to users' personal or company API accounts

**What to do instead:**
- Direct users to `@canva-ct/genai` for AI features
- Tell users to contact #creative-tech for other API needs
- Explain the security implications clearly

### For AI Features (OpenAI, Anthropic, Gemini, TTS)

Use the built-in `@canva-ct/genai` package - authentication is already handled securely:

```typescript
import { LLMStreamService } from "@canva-ct/genai/llm";
import { OpenRouterService } from "@canva-ct/genai/openrouter";

const llm = new LLMStreamService();
const openrouter = new OpenRouterService();
```

### For Other API Integrations

⚠️ **Contact #creative-tech on Slack before adding any API keys**

They will help you:
- Determine if the API key can be safely used in frontend
- Set up backend infrastructure if needed
- Implement proper security measures

## Test Data Guidelines

Use obviously fake data for prototypes:

```typescript
// ✅ Good - clearly fake data
const user = { name: "Linda Test", email: "linda@test.com", phone: "123-456-7890" };

// ❌ Bad - looks like real Canva data
const user = { name: "Linda Smith", email: "linda@canva.com", phone: "555-0123" };
```

## Git & GitHub Guidelines

- ✅ Use your Canva email address for GitHub (not personal email)
- ✅ Store code in the **Canvanauts** GitHub organization
- ❌ Never upload Canva code to personal GitHub repositories

## When to Pause and Ask User

ALWAYS pause before: backend functionality, external API calls, databases, authentication systems, or public endpoints.

### Message Patterns

**For API Keys:**
> ⚠️ Before adding any API key:
>
> **For AI features** (OpenAI, Anthropic, Gemini, TTS):
> - Use the built-in `@canva-ct/genai` package
> - Would you like me to help you set it up?
>
> **For other APIs**:
> - Please contact **#creative-tech** on Slack first
> - They'll help determine if the API key can be safely used
> - They'll guide you on proper setup and security measures
> - This is a frontend-only app, so all API keys will be publicly visible unless we use a backend proxy
>
> Should I help you set up AI features using @canva-ct/genai, or would you like to reach out to #creative-tech first?

**For Sharing Projects:**
> ⚠️ It looks like you want to find a way to share this project with others, that's really exciting! Please check out **#flying-fox** on Slack to see if it suits your needs. If you need further support, please reach out to the Slack channel **#creative-tech** for the best approach.

**When user attempts to save code to GitHub:**
> ⚠️ It looks like you're trying to upload your code to GitHub.
>
> **Important reminders:**
> - Use your **Canva email** for your GitHub account (not personal email)
> - Store the code in the **Canvanauts** organization repository
> - If you need help setting this up, contact **#creative-tech** on Slack

## Pre-Commit Security Checklist

Before committing code, verify:
- [ ] No hardcoded secrets in code, comments, or documentation
- [ ] AI features use @canva-ct/genai package (not custom API keys)

**If any check fails:** Stop immediately, alert user, suggest secure alternative based on the supported patterns in the rules, and wait for confirmation.

## Teaching Security Through Guardrails

When blocking risky behavior, explain:
- What the security risk is and why it's dangerous
- What the secure alternative is
- How it protects the user and Canva

### Key Explanations

**Why no hardcoded secrets:**
- Saved in version history forever (even if deleted later)
- Visible to anyone with code access
- Frontend code runs in browser - anyone can view it in DevTools
- For AI: use @canva-ct/genai; for other APIs: contact #creative-tech

**Why no infrastructure commands:**
- Changes need approval and tracking
- Direct changes bypass security reviews
- Mistakes can affect production systems

**Goals:** Educate, protect, guide, and empower security awareness.
